  <span id="freeText15193652051909347674" style="display:none">I read this shortly after reading Daniel Suarez's Daemon, and thought that of the two, Daemon was a much better book. The system run amok in this book was almost magical in how quickly it improved itself, and went from being an improved email grammar checker to a system that could... <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[order military systems, fix the stock market, and create world peace, <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span> all in a few months. Also, the plot completely depends on the fact that all of the people being affected (which includes world leaders and CEOs) never talk to each other face to face or on the phone, a critical part of almost all high-level political and business negotiations. I thought that some of the ideas that he brought up were interesting, but you can get most of those from the first few chapters and after that my interest waned severely. </span>
